01 9:02:19 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Will Code Red virus effect Verant's servers?</span><hr size=1> Tudamorf:<br>
<br>
If you don't think the price of the computer is higher because it includes software and os, you are mistaken.  Sure, the price of the software is much less than if you bought it boxed separately, but the cost is still there.  Why should I pay for an OS that I'm not going to use just because it comes on a computer and then turn around and buy another OS to install on it?)<br>
<br>
Linux is most likely going to be a viable alternative to Windows at some point (it's growing all the time).   However, our firm uses Visual FoxPro for our auditing and analysis work.  We have invested thousands of hours in developing the programs we use over the years (back before Linux was available), so using an alternate product is not feasible at this time.  And as far as I know FoxPro does not run under Linux, and probably never will.<br>
<br>
Win 3.1/95/98/ME is one product line, NT/2000/XP is another - Sure, 98 was an improvment over 95.  But tell me how ME was an improvement over 98?  Other than the fact that Gates is getting richer from making people upgrade.<br>
<br>
One thing that annoys me that I forgot to mention in my other post is that Microsoft is more and more assuming that people use the internet for everything and are designing their software with the assumption that people are always wired online.  This is especially true in Win XP and Office XP where web integration is almost seamless in everything you do.<br>
<br>
However, I use Office on a laptop at client sites all the time and have no web access.  Things like searching for files, or searching for help text are bogged down because it can't find an internet connection.  Sure it's only a couple seconds here and a couple seconds there, but those seconds add up to decrease my productivity, which I rely on to make money.<br>
<br>
I have a Pentium 5/300 computer with 128 megs of ram, yet it takes just as long to boot up as back in the days when I was using DOS 4.0 on a IBM XT.  This is without having any programs run at startup other than virus protection.<br>
<br>
I used to have a great respect for Microsoft, and have used their products for years.  However, the past couple years things seem to have gone downhill and since they seem to have skated by the Justice monopoly investigation, I think we haven't seen the worst yet.<br>
